  <static seed="105" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/AddingFractionsOfInches10.pg">
    <statement><p>A <m>2\times4</m> piece of lumber in your garage is <m>{52{\textstyle\frac{9}{16}}}</m> inches long. A second <m>2\times4</m> is <m>{33{\textstyle\frac{1}{16}}}</m> inches long. If you lay them end to end, what will the total length be?</p>
<p>The total length will be <fillin characters="7" name="AnSwEr0001"/> inches.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>85{\textstyle\frac{5}{8}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find the total length in inches, we add the two lengths together.</p>
<p><m>\begin{aligned}
    {52{\textstyle\frac{9}{16}}}+{33{\textstyle\frac{1}{16}}} \amp  = 52+\frac{9}{16}+33+\frac{1}{16}\\
                \amp  = 85+\frac{9}{16}+\frac{1}{16}\\
                \amp  = 85+{{\frac{5}{8}}}\\
                \amp  = {85{\textstyle\frac{5}{8}}}
\end{aligned}</m></p>
<p>So the total length is <m>{85{\textstyle\frac{5}{8}}}</m> inches.</p>
</solution>
